      <h2>Is Cannabis Legal in Madrid? The Private vs. Public Distinction</h2>

      <p>Spain does not have a single law that says "cannabis is legal." Instead, the legal framework rests on a constitutional distinction between <strong>private</strong> and <strong>public</strong> spaces — and understanding this distinction is the single most important thing for any tourist visiting Madrid in 2026.</p>

      <p>Under Article 18.1 of the Spanish Constitution, personal activities within private spaces are protected. The Constitutional Tribunal confirmed this principle in its landmark ruling STC 53/1985. When it comes to cannabis specifically, Spain never criminalized personal possession or consumption — only public acts.</p>

      <h3>What Is Legal</h3>
      <ul class="pillar-list">
        <li>Consuming cannabis inside a <strong>licensed private social club</strong> that operates as a non-profit association</li>
        <li>Growing small quantities of cannabis plants for personal use on private property (not visible from public spaces)</li>
        <li>Being a member of a registered cannabis association under Spain's right to free association</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>What Is Illegal (With Real Fines)</h3>
      <ul class="pillar-list">
        <li><strong>Public possession:</strong> Administrative fines from <strong>€601 to €30,000</strong> under the Ley de Seguridad Ciudadana (LO 4/2015), commonly known as the Ley Mordaza</li>
        <li><strong>Public consumption:</strong> Same fine range. Smoking a joint on a terrace, park bench, or sidewalk will get you fined</li>
        <li><strong>Street purchases:</strong> Buying from any street dealer is illegal regardless of amount. Police in Puerta del Sol, Plaza Mayor, and Gran Via actively enforce this</li>
        <li><strong>Trafficking:</strong> Selling cannabis carries criminal penalties under Article 368 of the Penal Code — up to 3 years in prison</li>
        <li><strong>Transporting outside a club:</strong> Even if you purchased legally inside a club, carrying cannabis on public streets constitutes public possession</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="pillar-callout pillar-callout--warning">
        <strong>Tourist reality check:</strong> Police in central Madrid tourist zones have been increasing enforcement since late 2025. We have personally witnessed fines being issued at Puerta del Sol, Retiro Park entrances, and near Santiago Bernabeu on match days. The fine starts at €601 — there is no warning system.
      </div>

