      <h2>How to Join a Cannabis Club as a Tourist in Madrid</h2>

      <p>You cannot walk into a legitimate cannabis club off the street. Every real club requires an invitation from an existing member, identity verification, and a membership process. This is not a bureaucratic hurdle — it is the legal foundation that keeps clubs operating. Any club that lets you walk in without these steps is either breaking the law or is a scam targeting tourists.</p>

      <h3>The 5-Step Process</h3>
      <ol class="pillar-steps">
        <li>
          <strong>Get a verified invitation</strong> — You need an invitation link or referral from a current member. The most reliable way for tourists is through verified invitation platforms like WeedMadrid.com, which connects you to clubs that specifically accept international visitors.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Present valid ID</strong> — Bring your passport (required for non-EU tourists) or EU national ID card. Spanish law requires clubs to verify you are at least 21 years old. Some clubs accept 18+, but most legitimate ones set the bar at 21.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Complete registration</strong> — You will fill out a membership form at the club. This includes your full name, nationality, date of birth, and a signature confirming you understand the club rules. This paperwork exists to protect both you and the club legally.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Pay the membership fee</strong> — One-time fees range from €20 to €50 depending on the club. This covers your registration and annual membership. It is separate from any product contributions you make inside.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Receive your membership card</strong> — You will get a physical or digital card that you must present each time you visit. Without it, you cannot re-enter — even as a paying member.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="pillar-callout">
        <strong>Tourist vs. Resident requirements:</strong> Tourists can join most clubs, but the process takes slightly longer (ID verification of foreign documents). Some clubs also require tourists to show proof of accommodation in Madrid — a hotel booking confirmation or Airbnb receipt. Residents with NIE/TIE have a faster registration process.
      </div>

