      <h2>Cannabis Tourist Scams in Madrid: What We Have Documented</h2>

      <p>Madrid has a growing problem with cannabis-related tourist scams. We have personally investigated and documented the most common ones operating in 2025-2026. Knowing these tactics before you arrive can save you hundreds of euros and a lot of frustration.</p>

      <h3>The 4 Most Common Scams</h3>
      <ol class="pillar-steps">
        <li>
          <strong>The street handshake dealer</strong> — Men approach tourists near Sol, Opera, and Lavapies with a friendly handshake that leaves a small piece of hash in your palm, then demand €20-€50 payment. The product is almost always fake (oregano, henna, or paraffin). If you refuse to pay, they become aggressive. Our advice: never accept anything placed in your hand.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Fake "cannabis clubs"</strong> — Unlicensed operations that call themselves clubs but are really just apartments or back rooms. They charge inflated membership fees (€80-€150), sell poor-quality product, and have zero legal standing. If raided, you have no legal protection as a "member." Red flag: any club that advertises openly on the street or on social media with a visible address.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>WhatsApp delivery services</strong> — Social media ads and hostel flyers promoting WhatsApp numbers for "cannabis delivery." These are always illegal street dealers using a digital front. Products are unregulated, deliveries often do not show up after payment, and you have given a stranger your phone number and hotel location.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The "free sample" trap</strong> — Someone offers you a free sample outside a metro station or in a park, then their associate appears claiming to be police demanding an on-the-spot fine (which is not how Spanish law works). This is pure extortion.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="pillar-callout pillar-callout--warning">
        <strong>5 signs of a legitimate club:</strong> registered association number (CIF), proper membership paperwork, no street advertising, staff who check ID every visit, and a physical location that does not change frequently. If any of these are missing, leave.
      </div>

