    <!-- 8. Safety Tips -->
    <section id="safety" class="section">
      <h2>Cannabis Safety Tips for Madrid Tourists</h2>

      <p>Beyond the legal and scam considerations, there are practical safety tips that will make your experience smoother and safer.</p>

      <h3>Before Your Trip</h3>
      <ul class="pillar-list">
        <li><strong>Arrange your club invitation before arriving in Madrid.</strong> Do not wait until you are on the ground. The registration process is faster if you have a verified invitation link ready.</li>
        <li><strong>Bring your passport everywhere.</strong> You need it for club registration, and if police stop you for any reason, having ID avoids complications.</li>
        <li><strong>Download offline maps.</strong> Club addresses are often in side streets without obvious signage. Google Maps or CityMapper with offline Madrid maps will save you from wandering.</li>
        <li><strong>Carry cash in euros.</strong> ATMs at the airport charge 5-8% fees. Withdraw from city-center ATMs (Santander, BBVA, CaixaBank) for better rates.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>During Your Visit</h3>
      <ul class="pillar-list">
        <li><strong>Consume only inside the club.</strong> Do not smoke on the walk back to your hotel. Do not keep leftovers in your pocket "for later." The legal protection exists only within the club walls.</li>
        <li><strong>Start low, go slow.</strong> Spanish cannabis — especially club-grade product — tends to be stronger than what many tourists are accustomed to. Communicate your experience level to staff and start with a lower-THC strain if unsure.</li>
        <li><strong>Do not mix with alcohol excessively.</strong> Madrid nightlife encourages mixing, but overconsumption of cannabis plus alcohol is the number one cause of tourist medical incidents we have tracked.</li>
        <li><strong>Know your metro route home.</strong> Madrid Metro runs until 1:30 AM (2:00 AM on weekends). After that, night buses (buhos) run from Cibeles. Plan your exit strategy before consuming.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>If Something Goes Wrong</h3>
      <p>If you feel unwell after consuming, tell club staff immediately — experienced clubs have dealt with this before and can help. If you are approached by police on the street, remain calm, show your ID, and do not consent to a search if you have nothing on you. If you are fined, do not pay on the spot — fines are processed administratively and you can appeal. For medical emergencies, call <strong>112</strong> (Spain's universal emergency number).</p>
    </section>

