      <p>The biggest advantage of Madrid is the experience itself. Amsterdam coffee shops have become overcrowded tourist traps — especially in the Red Light District area. Madrid clubs offer a more authentic, relaxed atmosphere because they are not designed as tourist attractions. You sit in a lounge with local Spaniards, not a room full of British stag parties. The trade-off is that access requires more planning (you need an invitation in advance), but many tourists prefer that barrier because it creates a better environment inside.</p>

      <p>Amsterdam still wins on convenience — you can walk into a coffee shop with no preparation. But with the ongoing Dutch political discussions about restricting tourist access to coffee shops (the wietpas system that has been debated since 2012), Madrid is increasingly positioned as the more stable long-term destination for cannabis tourism in Europe.</p>
