      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Cannabis in Madrid</h2>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Is cannabis legal in Madrid for tourists?</summary>
        <p>Cannabis is decriminalized for private use in Spain. Public consumption and street purchases remain illegal with fines starting at €601. Tourists can legally consume cannabis only inside licensed private social clubs through a valid membership invitation. You must be 21+ with a valid passport.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How do I get into a cannabis club in Madrid?</summary>
        <p>You need a verified invitation from an existing club member, a valid passport or EU ID proving you are 21+, and must complete the registration process at the club (including paying a one-time membership fee of €20-€50). The most reliable way for tourists to get an invitation is through verified platforms like WeedMadrid.com.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What are the fines for buying cannabis on the street?</summary>
        <p>Fines range from €601 to €30,000 under the Ley de Seguridad Ciudadana (LO 4/2015). Police in central Madrid tourist areas actively enforce these laws. There is no warning system — the minimum fine is €601 on first offense.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Can I take cannabis from a club back to my hotel?</summary>
        <p>No. Transporting cannabis outside club premises is illegal. Even if you obtained it legally inside a licensed club, carrying it on public streets constitutes public possession. Consumption must happen within the private club space. Some tourists attempt this and risk fines starting at €601.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How much does a cannabis club cost in Madrid?</summary>
        <p>One-time membership fees range from €20 to €50. Inside the club, flower contributions run €6-€16 per gram depending on the club tier and strain. Hash is €5-€22 per gram. Pre-rolls cost €3-€12. For a typical 3-day tourist visit, budget €80-€140 total including membership, products, and drinks.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Are Madrid cannabis clubs safe for tourists?</summary>
        <p>Legitimate clubs with proper registration (CIF number), membership processes, and staff who verify ID are safe. The key is getting in through a verified invitation — not through street promoters, social media ads, or WhatsApp delivery services. Clubs that follow proper protocols provide legal protection for members consuming on premises.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is the best neighborhood for cannabis clubs in Madrid?</summary>
        <p>Malasana offers the highest concentration of tourist-friendly clubs with good metro connections (Tribunal, Noviciado). Chamberi is ideal for a quieter, more local experience with very low scam risk. Avoid lingering in Lavapies near Tirso de Molina metro where street dealer activity is highest.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Do I need to speak Spanish to join a cannabis club?</summary>
        <p>Most tourist-friendly clubs in central Madrid have English-speaking staff. Registration forms may be in Spanish but staff will guide you through them. Having a translation app is helpful but not essential if you choose a club that caters to international visitors.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Can I smoke cannabis in my Madrid hotel room?</summary>
        <p>This is a gray area. Legally, your hotel room is a private space — but hotel policies almost universally prohibit smoking of any kind. If you trigger a smoke alarm or another guest complains, the hotel can charge you a cleaning fee (€100-€300) and potentially report you. We strongly advise against it.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Is Madrid better than Amsterdam for cannabis tourism?</summary>
        <p>It depends on what you value. Amsterdam offers walk-in convenience with no invitation needed. Madrid offers higher product quality, lower prices, a more authentic atmosphere, better food and weather, and no current threat of tourist bans. Madrid requires more planning but delivers a better overall experience for many travelers.</p>
      </details>
